So you've been talking all
about the happiness aspect,

00:32:59.580 --> 00:33:02.090
but you also mentioned
the term self-actualized.

00:33:02.090 --> 00:33:03.900
And I was curious
of your perspective

00:33:03.900 --> 00:33:06.412
on how you view the
difference between those two.

00:33:06.412 --> 00:33:10.860
And to the point about a life
of trying to find meaning,

00:33:10.860 --> 00:33:14.286
but about an effort to try and
get to better know yourself

00:33:14.286 --> 00:33:16.000
through that
self-actualized review.

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:16.833
RUTH WHIPPMAN: Yeah.

00:33:16.833 --> 00:33:20.370
So I think it's about balance,
because obviously getting

00:33:20.370 --> 00:33:23.490
to know who you are
and becoming the best

00:33:23.490 --> 00:33:25.940
self that you can be-- all of
those things are important.

00:33:25.940 --> 00:33:28.362
And to work out
who you are and how

00:33:28.362 --> 00:33:30.320
to work with that, that's
very, very important.

00:33:30.320 --> 00:33:31.903
But I think what's
happened in America

00:33:31.903 --> 00:33:35.400
is that the balance has
somehow got out of whack.

00:33:35.400 --> 00:33:37.380
So we're putting
self-actualisation

00:33:37.380 --> 00:33:39.150
above connection.

00:33:39.150 --> 00:33:42.961
So the idea is that we engineer
happiness from the inside out.

00:33:42.961 --> 00:33:45.210
That if you can perfectly
know yourself and understand

00:33:45.210 --> 00:33:45.380
yourself--

00:33:45.380 --> 00:33:47.088
I don't know if you've
heard this phrase,

00:33:47.088 --> 00:33:48.340
happiness comes from within.

00:33:48.340 --> 00:33:52.650
It's actually impossible to
get a result on a Google search

00:33:52.650 --> 00:33:55.399
that tells you the
opposite, because I typed it

00:33:55.399 --> 00:33:56.190
in that happiness--

00:33:56.190 --> 00:33:57.390
I was going to do some--

00:33:57.390 --> 00:33:59.765
at one point I was thinking
of doing some slides for this

00:33:59.765 --> 00:34:02.310
and I typed in meme
happiness comes from within.

00:34:02.310 --> 00:34:06.030
You got 1,000 results of all
these different memes saying

00:34:06.030 --> 00:34:07.380
variations on this.

00:34:07.380 --> 00:34:09.480
If you type in meme
in an image search,

00:34:09.480 --> 00:34:11.310
happiness comes
from other people,

00:34:11.310 --> 00:34:14.190
every single result seemingly or
at least on the front page that

00:34:14.190 --> 00:34:16.760
comes back says, happiness does
not come from other people,

00:34:16.760 --> 00:34:17.926
happiness comes from within.

00:34:17.926 --> 00:34:20.219
[LAUGHTER]

00:34:20.219 --> 00:34:22.639
And it's almost
like-- and so I think

00:34:22.639 --> 00:34:24.170
the balance has got wrong.

00:34:24.170 --> 00:34:26.260
So I'm not saying
that people should not

00:34:26.260 --> 00:34:28.480
try to understand themselves,
reflect on themselves,

00:34:28.480 --> 00:34:28.980
all of that.

00:34:28.980 --> 00:34:30.389
That's obviously
important, but I

00:34:30.389 --> 00:34:34.469
think the emphasis has
gone wrong somewhere.

00:34:34.469 --> 00:34:36.659
I think if we make
connection and other people

00:34:36.659 --> 00:34:38.889
are starting point
and then throw

00:34:38.889 --> 00:34:40.500
in a bit of
self-actualization, rather

00:34:40.500 --> 00:34:44.652
than having the balance
so skewed the other way.

00:34:44.652 --> 00:34:45.600
Thanks.

00:34:45.600 --> 00:34:46.427
Oh, hey.

00:34:46.427 --> 00:34:48.510
AUDIENCE: So you were
talking about the importance

00:34:48.510 --> 00:34:49.969
of social connections.

00:34:49.969 --> 00:34:51.810
I think there are two
types I can imagine.

00:34:51.810 --> 00:34:53.909
First, there are, for
example, close friends

00:34:53.909 --> 00:34:56.280
who I spend a lot of
time interacting with

00:34:56.280 --> 00:34:57.600
and I have deep connection.

00:34:57.600 --> 00:35:00.070
And then there are just
people I barely know.

00:35:00.070 --> 00:35:03.000
So it's just hard to
have many close friends,

00:35:03.000 --> 00:35:04.859
because it takes a lot of time.

00:35:04.859 --> 00:35:06.900
But you can have a lot of
people you barely know.

00:35:06.900 --> 00:35:11.124
Is there any distinction which
type of relationships is more--

00:35:11.124 --> 00:35:12.540
what's the difference
between them

00:35:12.540 --> 00:35:14.970
and how do they influence
happiness in different ways?

00:35:14.970 --> 00:35:17.040
Close relationships
and more meaningful

00:35:17.040 --> 00:35:18.690
or just know as
many people you can?

00:35:18.690 --> 00:35:20.460
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:20.460 --> 00:35:22.479
RUTH WHIPPMAN: So both
are actually important,

00:35:22.479 --> 00:35:23.020
surprisingly.

00:35:23.020 --> 00:35:24.900
So it goes without
saying, I think,

00:35:24.900 --> 00:35:27.000
that close friendships
and really supportive

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:29.950
relationships are more
important than the women who

00:35:29.950 --> 00:35:33.760
sells you your newspaper
in the morning or whatever.

00:35:33.760 --> 00:35:38.460
And that's really the key is
focusing on a few very close

00:35:38.460 --> 00:35:40.085
supportive relationships.

00:35:40.085 --> 00:35:41.490
But there is pretty
good evidence

00:35:41.490 --> 00:35:44.960
to show that having lots of--

00:35:44.960 --> 00:35:47.550
there is a technical term
for it-- but small social

00:35:47.550 --> 00:35:48.340
connections also.

00:35:48.340 --> 00:35:49.900
And being part of
a wider community

00:35:49.900 --> 00:35:51.720
and feeling invested
in a community

00:35:51.720 --> 00:35:55.050
also has a big impact on
our happiness as well.

00:35:55.050 --> 00:35:58.380
So just feeling that
we're part of something

00:35:58.380 --> 00:36:01.430
bigger than ourselves, I think.

00:36:01.430 --> 00:36:03.150
So I think in
aggregate it might not

00:36:03.150 --> 00:36:05.316
be that every single one
of those little connections

00:36:05.316 --> 00:36:08.070
really is that meaningful,
but overall, I think

00:36:08.070 --> 00:36:09.700
they can make a big difference.

00:36:09.700 --> 00:36:11.310
SPEAKER: And I thought there
was an interesting point

00:36:11.310 --> 00:36:13.470
in the book, not to give
too many details away,

00:36:13.470 --> 00:36:17.460
but you quote Thomas Jefferson
and the pursuit of happiness.

00:36:17.460 --> 00:36:19.800
And your interpretation
it's not so much

00:36:19.800 --> 00:36:22.110
pursuing this inward
happiness, which

00:36:22.110 --> 00:36:24.780
is perfected from all
my self-actualization,

00:36:24.780 --> 00:36:27.385
but rather pursuing
a happiness which

00:36:27.385 --> 00:36:29.010
makes you part of a
community and makes

00:36:29.010 --> 00:36:30.260
you part of that larger whole.

00:36:30.260 --> 00:36:31.051
RUTH WHIPPMAN: Yes.

00:36:31.051 --> 00:36:33.657
I mean, I think that's pretty
clear that the founding fathers

00:36:33.657 --> 00:36:36.240
weren't really thinking about a
self-help workshop when they--

00:36:36.240 --> 00:36:36.970
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:36.970 --> 00:36:38.850
I mean, that's taking
it to an extreme.

00:36:38.850 --> 00:36:42.090
But yes, they were talking about
civic engagement and community

00:36:42.090 --> 00:36:46.386
and that was very much being
part of a larger thing.

00:36:46.386 --> 00:36:47.967
SPEAKER: Cool.

00:36:47.967 --> 00:36:48.800
RUTH WHIPPMAN: Yeah.

00:36:48.800 --> 00:36:49.880
Hi.

00:36:49.880 --> 00:36:52.380
AUDIENCE: One more.

00:36:52.380 --> 00:36:56.012
I wonder if you upon writing
your book, if you touch on that

00:36:56.012 --> 00:36:58.220
or what would you think
about-- or if you've noticed,

00:36:58.220 --> 00:37:01.050
I'm not from here either.

00:37:01.050 --> 00:37:04.730
And I wonder if you
noticed that there

00:37:04.730 --> 00:37:09.850
seems to be some bragging
around mentioning or just

00:37:09.850 --> 00:37:12.500
even implying that you're busy.

00:37:12.500 --> 00:37:17.480
And people-- I find it very hard
here to just call a friend up

00:37:17.480 --> 00:37:19.110
and say, hey, are
you up for a beer?

00:37:19.110 --> 00:37:20.720
It's almost
virtually impossible.

00:37:20.720 --> 00:37:23.780
And where I come from,
it's like we're adults,

00:37:23.780 --> 00:37:26.740
we have these lives,
but it's just easier.

00:37:26.740 --> 00:37:31.090
And I have almost become
that myself too, where--

00:37:31.090 --> 00:37:33.340
RUTH WHIPPMAN: Everything
is great and wonderful idea.

00:37:33.340 --> 00:37:36.400
AUDIENCE: --And the kids,
and I work full time.

00:37:36.400 --> 00:37:38.690
And so yeah, it's also
hard for me sometimes.

00:37:38.690 --> 00:37:41.530
But I get the sense
too, sometimes

00:37:41.530 --> 00:37:44.630
that I feel this inner pride
of saying, well, no I'm busy,

00:37:44.630 --> 00:37:47.470
and tonight can't
make it work or not.

00:37:47.470 --> 00:37:49.670
And I'm like, yeah,
I'm a busy person.

00:37:49.670 --> 00:37:51.170
And then I'm like,
I feel like shit.

00:37:51.170 --> 00:37:55.280
I haven't had a beer in
a long time with anyone.

00:37:55.280 --> 00:37:56.347
And I don't know.

00:37:56.347 --> 00:37:57.180
RUTH WHIPPMAN: Yeah.

00:37:57.180 --> 00:37:59.600
I mean it's so easy to
put just socializing down

00:37:59.600 --> 00:38:02.240
to the absolute bottom of
the priority list, isn't it?

00:38:02.240 --> 00:38:04.640
I mean, if you have a full
time job, you work hard--

00:38:04.640 --> 00:38:05.599
I think, there's this--

00:38:05.599 --> 00:38:07.390
I mean, we didn't
actually talk about this,

00:38:07.390 --> 00:38:09.660
but it's something that
I touched on in the book.

00:38:09.660 --> 00:38:12.250
That now what used to be
called work-life balance,

00:38:12.250 --> 00:38:14.810
they're now calling
work-life integration,

00:38:14.810 --> 00:38:16.345
which just makes my heart sink.

00:38:16.345 --> 00:38:17.988
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:17.988 --> 00:38:20.749
This seems to be more work.

00:38:20.749 --> 00:38:22.790
That you have to have your
phone on all the time,

00:38:22.790 --> 00:38:24.380
that you are answerable,
you're always on the clock.

00:38:24.380 --> 00:38:26.546
And that we're merging all
these parts of our lives.

00:38:26.546 --> 00:38:29.840
So there's very little
socializing or communicating

00:38:29.840 --> 00:38:33.645
or whatever with friends
that is totally free of work

00:38:33.645 --> 00:38:35.270
and free of
responsibilities in the way

00:38:35.270 --> 00:38:37.240
that perhaps it used to be.

00:38:37.240 --> 00:38:39.560
And I mean there's
this really chilling--

00:38:39.560 --> 00:38:41.789
I thought chilling
statistic, which is the--

00:38:41.789 --> 00:38:44.330
I don't know if you've heard of
the American time use survey,

00:38:44.330 --> 00:38:46.490
but they just categorize
how people literally spend

00:38:46.490 --> 00:38:48.480
every moment of their day.

00:38:48.480 --> 00:38:51.110
And every activity
that you can think

00:38:51.110 --> 00:38:53.600
of-- working, sleeping,
driving, having sex, whatever--

00:38:53.600 --> 00:38:55.240
is all categorized.

00:38:55.240 --> 00:38:57.200
And there's a category
on the survey called

00:38:57.200 --> 00:38:59.340
socializing and communicating.

00:38:59.340 --> 00:39:01.180
And it doesn't just
cover the good stuff.

00:39:01.180 --> 00:39:03.002
So it's not just the
lovely heart to heart

00:39:03.002 --> 00:39:04.460
that you have with
your best friend

00:39:04.460 --> 00:39:07.190
or this adoring conversation
with your boyfriend

00:39:07.190 --> 00:39:08.030
or girlfriend.

00:39:08.030 --> 00:39:10.340
It's all the arguing, the
nagging, the bitching,

00:39:10.340 --> 00:39:12.950
the whining, everything,
all thrown in together.

00:39:12.950 --> 00:39:15.820
So as long as there's more
than one adult present

00:39:15.820 --> 00:39:18.884
and it's not an incidental
part of something else.

00:39:18.884 --> 00:39:20.300
Does anyone want
to hazard a guess

00:39:20.300 --> 00:39:22.940
how much time we spent
on that category per day,

00:39:22.940 --> 00:39:26.750
the average American?

00:39:26.750 --> 00:39:28.670
AUDIENCE: 30 minutes.

00:39:28.670 --> 00:39:29.640
RUTH WHIPPMAN: Yeah.

00:39:29.640 --> 00:39:31.140
It's about 30 minutes a day.

00:39:31.140 --> 00:39:37.590
So put another way, we know this
is the single most important

00:39:37.590 --> 00:39:39.690
pillar of our
happiness, but yet we

00:39:39.690 --> 00:39:42.450
spend 23 and 1/2 hours
out of every day not

00:39:42.450 --> 00:39:46.180
doing that, doing something
completely different.

00:39:46.180 --> 00:39:47.610
So I found that pretty scary.

00:39:50.590 --> 00:39:51.090
Hi.

00:39:51.090 --> 00:39:53.780
AUDIENCE: Thanks for your talk.

00:39:53.780 --> 00:39:56.320
Did you happen to see the
article in "The New York Times

00:39:56.320 --> 00:39:58.210
Magazine" this last weekend?

00:39:58.210 --> 00:39:59.930
It was called, "The
Kids Who Can't."

00:39:59.930 --> 00:40:01.480
Which is like a mean title.

00:40:01.480 --> 00:40:02.980
RUTH WHIPPMAN: Oh,
I don't think so.

00:40:02.980 --> 00:40:05.170
AUDIENCE: It was about
anxiety with millennials,

00:40:05.170 --> 00:40:08.690
and especially, the
youngest millennials.

00:40:08.690 --> 00:40:11.464
It was saying that-- it was
talking about this phenomenon.

00:40:11.464 --> 00:40:12.880
So first of all,
I wondered if you

00:40:12.880 --> 00:40:14.296
came across this
in your research,

00:40:14.296 --> 00:40:16.422
anxiety being a bigger
problem with younger people?

00:40:16.422 --> 00:40:17.212
RUTH WHIPPMAN: Yes.

00:40:17.212 --> 00:40:17.950
Definitely.

00:40:17.950 --> 00:40:20.750
AUDIENCE: And then have any
guesses of how to explain it,

00:40:20.750 --> 00:40:23.320
it mentioned the social media
phenomenon, which I think

00:40:23.320 --> 00:40:25.480
is right on the money
and you touched on that.

00:40:25.480 --> 00:40:28.560
But another thing it
talked about was how--

00:40:28.560 --> 00:40:32.380
I don't love this word, but it
said that the youngest people

00:40:32.380 --> 00:40:34.946
are being coddled in the
sense that it's common now

00:40:34.946 --> 00:40:36.820
if a kid is feeling
anxious that they're just

00:40:36.820 --> 00:40:39.670
allowed to stay home from
school or that they have

00:40:39.670 --> 00:40:42.610
their own dedicated
entrance to avoid

00:40:42.610 --> 00:40:44.817
the stressors of the
main entrance at school.

00:40:44.817 --> 00:40:46.900
And that was one of the
ideas that was put forward

00:40:46.900 --> 00:40:49.990
as to why this is actually
having a negative effect

00:40:49.990 --> 00:40:52.610
and keeping them in
this spiral of anxiety.

00:40:52.610 --> 00:40:54.530
So I wondered what you
thought about that?

00:40:54.530 --> 00:40:54.820
RUTH WHIPPMAN: Yeah.

00:40:54.820 --> 00:40:56.153
I think that's absolutely right.

00:40:56.153 --> 00:40:58.140
I mean, and I notice
it in myself as well.

00:40:58.140 --> 00:40:59.020
I have two kids.

00:40:59.020 --> 00:41:05.920
And my oldest son, he goes to
this drama group on a Thursday,

00:41:05.920 --> 00:41:09.589
and he decided he doesn't like
it and he doesn't want to go.

00:41:09.589 --> 00:41:11.380
And that he's got some
anxiety around that.

00:41:11.380 --> 00:41:14.160
And instantly I think,
ooh, we've got to stop,

00:41:14.160 --> 00:41:15.165
he doesn't have to go.

00:41:15.165 --> 00:41:16.540
Why should he have
to go to that?

00:41:16.540 --> 00:41:19.206
And it's very easy to think--

00:41:19.206 --> 00:41:21.080
and I was about to pull
him out of this thing

00:41:21.080 --> 00:41:22.930
and I go what on
earth am I doing?

00:41:22.930 --> 00:41:26.152
I mean, and I look back at
my childhood and probably

00:41:26.152 --> 00:41:29.110
a good 70%, 80% of the
stuff that I didn't really

00:41:29.110 --> 00:41:31.930
want to be doing that much
and nobody was suggesting

00:41:31.930 --> 00:41:34.100
that I would not be
doing it because of that.

00:41:34.100 --> 00:41:36.070
And there's a
balance and whatever.

00:41:36.070 --> 00:41:39.220
And I think it is good that we
consider kids' feelings more

00:41:39.220 --> 00:41:41.630
now and that we
consider their emotions

00:41:41.630 --> 00:41:43.020
and treat them as important.

00:41:43.020 --> 00:41:44.241
And I do think that.

00:41:44.241 --> 00:41:46.740
But absolutely, I think there
is this tendency and this idea

00:41:46.740 --> 00:41:49.180
that everything has to be
magical and wonderful for kids

00:41:49.180 --> 00:41:53.380
and that we remove negative
experiences from their path.

00:41:53.380 --> 00:41:57.245
That is very damaging for sure.

00:41:57.245 --> 00:41:58.330
AUDIENCE: How you doing?

00:41:58.330 --> 00:41:59.112
Thanks for coming.

00:41:59.112 --> 00:42:00.570
So my question
actually in relation

00:42:00.570 --> 00:42:02.040
to that right there along
with the gentleman's

00:42:02.040 --> 00:42:04.440
question over here about
sharing the connection and also

00:42:04.440 --> 00:42:05.520
time usage.

00:42:05.520 --> 00:42:07.730
So you talk about the sense
of community obviously

00:42:07.730 --> 00:42:10.650
and to go along with these
younger generations being

00:42:10.650 --> 00:42:14.130
a little more hyperactive or
stuck in these social media

00:42:14.130 --> 00:42:15.770
and everything.

00:42:15.770 --> 00:42:19.166
It seems to be a stereotype of
millennials that they're ADD,

00:42:19.166 --> 00:42:21.040
they can't keep their
attention for anything.

00:42:21.040 --> 00:42:24.420
So this idea of fragmentation
of not only your work and life

00:42:24.420 --> 00:42:27.110
balance and everything, but
also your personal interests.

00:42:27.110 --> 00:42:31.200
Do you find any correlation
between simplification

00:42:31.200 --> 00:42:34.740
or really focusing on a
specific interest of yours

00:42:34.740 --> 00:42:36.840
in regards to this
idea of having

00:42:36.840 --> 00:42:38.910
too many communities
or too many friendships

00:42:38.910 --> 00:42:40.860
that you don't actually get the
value out of it that you might?

00:42:40.860 --> 00:42:42.270
Or is there a threshold
or correlation

00:42:42.270 --> 00:42:44.610
to this idea that some of
these less developed countries

00:42:44.610 --> 00:42:46.770
have less things to worry
about-- not necessarily

00:42:46.770 --> 00:42:47.970
less things to worry about
and very important things

00:42:47.970 --> 00:42:50.280
to worry about-- but this
idea that maybe they're just

00:42:50.280 --> 00:42:52.350
not over-exerting where
their interests lie

00:42:52.350 --> 00:42:54.757
and trying to do too much
or have too many communities

00:42:54.757 --> 00:42:55.840
to really get invested in.

00:42:55.840 --> 00:42:57.548
RUTH WHIPPMAN: Yeah,
and too much choice.

00:42:57.548 --> 00:43:00.665
And I think we live in this
very consumerist world where

00:43:00.665 --> 00:43:02.790
we have so much choice for
everything all the time.

00:43:02.790 --> 00:43:04.664
And I think that can
sometimes be paralyzing.

00:43:04.664 --> 00:43:07.320
That if you can be anything--

00:43:07.320 --> 00:43:09.900
if we are all told, be
whatever you want to be,

00:43:09.900 --> 00:43:14.250
follow your passion, find your
path, you can do anything.

00:43:14.250 --> 00:43:18.240
I think sometimes you think,
oh my god, I can't do anything,

00:43:18.240 --> 00:43:23.070
because it's just the
expectation is so high of what

00:43:23.070 --> 00:43:24.870
happiness should look like.

00:43:24.870 --> 00:43:28.800
And so many choices, so
many demands on our time

00:43:28.800 --> 00:43:30.320
and attention, I
think absolutely

00:43:30.320 --> 00:43:31.654
that it can be quite paralyzing.

00:43:31.654 --> 00:43:33.570
AUDIENCE: Yeah, sorry,
just a quick follow-up.

00:43:33.570 --> 00:43:35.250
Meaning, more
specifically, do you

00:43:35.250 --> 00:43:37.050
think that there's
value in trying

00:43:37.050 --> 00:43:39.030
to find a few
interests, as opposed

00:43:39.030 --> 00:43:41.140
to just diversifying that a bit?

00:43:41.140 --> 00:43:41.970
RUTH WHIPPMAN: Lots
of different things?

00:43:41.970 --> 00:43:42.270
That's interesting.

00:43:42.270 --> 00:43:42.960
Yeah, I don't know.

00:43:42.960 --> 00:43:44.501
I didn't look into
that specifically,

00:43:44.501 --> 00:43:47.240
but I think that probably
depends on the individual

00:43:47.240 --> 00:43:47.740
as well.

00:43:47.740 --> 00:43:51.030
I think some people really have
a very deep and abiding passion

00:43:51.030 --> 00:43:53.820
for one thing and that
really brings them happiness

00:43:53.820 --> 00:43:55.247
and meaning to follow that.

00:43:55.247 --> 00:43:57.330
And other people will try
lots of different things

00:43:57.330 --> 00:43:58.540
throughout the course of life.

00:43:58.540 --> 00:43:59.400
And same with friendships.

00:43:59.400 --> 00:44:01.350
I think somebody over
here asked about-- you

00:44:01.350 --> 00:44:04.962
asked about is it one
handful of close friends

00:44:04.962 --> 00:44:06.670
or is it knowing lots
and lots of people.

00:44:06.670 --> 00:44:09.640
And I think that is to do
with individual personality,

00:44:09.640 --> 00:44:13.190
really what it comes down to.

