00:45:04.190 --> 00:45:05.255
we were talking about before.

00:45:05.255 --> 00:45:05.670
RUTH WHIPPMAN: Yeah, before.

00:45:05.670 --> 00:45:06.000
Yeah.

00:45:06.000 --> 00:45:06.645
AUDIENCE: "Altered Traits?"

00:45:06.645 --> 00:45:06.910
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:45:06.910 --> 00:45:07.767
"Altered Traits."

00:45:07.767 --> 00:45:09.350
AUDIENCE: And so I
guess I was curious

00:45:09.350 --> 00:45:11.841
in your own findings, this is--

00:45:11.841 --> 00:45:13.340
RUTH WHIPPMAN: So
this is a really--

00:45:13.340 --> 00:45:17.144
this has been one of the most
controversial things actually--

00:45:17.144 --> 00:45:18.560
this whole thing
about meditation.

00:45:18.560 --> 00:45:20.900
Every time I ever
bring up meditation,

00:45:20.900 --> 00:45:23.030
I get a million emails
from angry meditators

00:45:23.030 --> 00:45:25.071
all over the world wanting
to run me out of town.

00:45:25.071 --> 00:45:26.040
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:26.040 --> 00:45:28.640
So I think there's
a few things there.

00:45:28.640 --> 00:45:30.620
I think neuroscience is
much more complicated

00:45:30.620 --> 00:45:33.120
than popular neuroscience
would allow us to believe.

00:45:33.120 --> 00:45:35.950
So when we say, something
changes the brain,

00:45:35.950 --> 00:45:38.450
it sounds amazingly
impressive, but pretty much

00:45:38.450 --> 00:45:40.400
everything we do
changes the brain.

00:45:40.400 --> 00:45:43.430
So from going to the bathroom
or to just sitting here

00:45:43.430 --> 00:45:45.170
now to hearing your questions.

00:45:45.170 --> 00:45:46.770
Everything we do
changes the brain,

00:45:46.770 --> 00:45:48.930
because that's the
nature of the brain.

00:45:48.930 --> 00:45:50.990
But so meditation and
mindfulness-- there

00:45:50.990 --> 00:45:53.120
have been many
thousands of studies

00:45:53.120 --> 00:45:55.220
done into the effects
of these things.

00:45:55.220 --> 00:46:00.960
And the results have been, I
would say from my experience,

00:46:00.960 --> 00:46:03.240
that not that there are no
effects of these things,

00:46:03.240 --> 00:46:05.120
but they have been quite
strongly over-hyped.

00:46:05.120 --> 00:46:06.500
So there was a
meta-analysis that

00:46:06.500 --> 00:46:09.680
came out a year
or two ago, which

00:46:09.680 --> 00:46:12.920
looked at all of these studies
and found that out of something

00:46:12.920 --> 00:46:16.550
like 1,800 studies,
only 40 of them

00:46:16.550 --> 00:46:18.470
actually had a controlled
comparison group.

00:46:18.470 --> 00:46:20.496
So I don't know how much
people know about how

00:46:20.496 --> 00:46:21.620
these kind of studies work.

00:46:21.620 --> 00:46:24.422
But comparing a
group of people who

00:46:24.422 --> 00:46:26.630
meditates to a group of
people who don't do anything,

00:46:26.630 --> 00:46:30.161
isn't really a fair
comparison because there's so

00:46:30.161 --> 00:46:31.910
many other factors
that could be going on.

00:46:31.910 --> 00:46:33.284
There could be
placebo effect, it

00:46:33.284 --> 00:46:37.220
could be the effect of having
a social connection, whatever.

00:46:37.220 --> 00:46:40.490
When meditation is compared
to a control group where

00:46:40.490 --> 00:46:42.380
they are doing
something comparable,

00:46:42.380 --> 00:46:46.230
a reasonable control group,
meditation performs no better

00:46:46.230 --> 00:46:50.420
and often worse than
something like exercise,

00:46:50.420 --> 00:46:55.100
listening to spiritual
audiotapes, any kind of sham

00:46:55.100 --> 00:46:58.070
control where you're
just putting something

00:46:58.070 --> 00:46:59.350
to be a controlled condition.

00:46:59.350 --> 00:47:01.940
So I think we need to
approach it with caution.

00:47:01.940 --> 00:47:03.971
Which isn't to say
that for many people

00:47:03.971 --> 00:47:06.470
it's an extremely meaningful
and important part of their day

00:47:06.470 --> 00:47:09.410
and something that they
really get a lot from.

00:47:09.410 --> 00:47:10.250
And that's great.

00:47:10.250 --> 00:47:12.040
But I think once we
start rolling it out

00:47:12.040 --> 00:47:13.706
as the answer to
everything, then that's

00:47:13.706 --> 00:47:17.309
where it becomes problematic.

00:47:17.309 --> 00:47:18.725
AUDIENCE: Sorry
one more question.

00:47:18.725 --> 00:47:19.010
RUTH WHIPPMAN: Sure.

00:47:19.010 --> 00:47:19.510
Yeah.

00:47:19.510 --> 00:47:21.489
AUDIENCE: So while
you're writing this book

00:47:21.489 --> 00:47:23.030
and doing research
was there anything

00:47:23.030 --> 00:47:25.017
that you found was effective?

00:47:25.017 --> 00:47:25.850
RUTH WHIPPMAN: Yeah.

00:47:25.850 --> 00:47:27.530
I mean, I think it comes back--

00:47:27.530 --> 00:47:29.613
this is just keep banging
on about the same thing.

00:47:29.613 --> 00:47:33.640
But really it does come down
to connecting with other people

00:47:33.640 --> 00:47:38.300
and doing that in a way
that's most meaningful to you.

00:47:38.300 --> 00:47:41.990
But literally
spending more time--

00:47:41.990 --> 00:47:44.060
seeing that we
spend half an hour

00:47:44.060 --> 00:47:45.800
of our day socializing,
communicating,

00:47:45.800 --> 00:47:47.675
as opposed to three
hours watching television

00:47:47.675 --> 00:47:49.380
or being on the
internet or whatever,

00:47:49.380 --> 00:47:51.980
and actually just trying
to up those minute.

00:47:51.980 --> 00:47:56.390
To just spend more time doing
it and nurture the relationships

00:47:56.390 --> 00:47:56.990
that we have.

00:47:56.990 --> 00:47:59.930
I think that really is far
and away the best thing you

00:47:59.930 --> 00:48:01.654
can do for your own happiness.

00:48:01.654 --> 00:48:03.320
AUDIENCE: Sorry, to
clarify, I meant out

00:48:03.320 --> 00:48:05.330
