00:48:51.960 --> 00:48:54.687
When measuring happiness, how
do you correct to the others--

00:48:54.687 --> 00:48:55.520
there's a question--

00:48:55.520 --> 00:48:57.091
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:48:57.091 --> 00:48:58.590
When measuring
happiness, how do you

00:48:58.590 --> 00:49:03.801
correct for cultural differences
in what being somewhat very et

00:49:03.801 --> 00:49:05.490
cetera happy?

00:49:05.490 --> 00:49:08.327
I guess how do you add a
measure for cultural differences

00:49:08.327 --> 00:49:09.410
when looking at happiness.

00:49:09.410 --> 00:49:10.080
RUTH WHIPPMAN: Yeah.

00:49:10.080 --> 00:49:11.621
That's a really
interesting question.

00:49:11.621 --> 00:49:13.831
I mean, there's a lot
of research on this,

00:49:13.831 --> 00:49:15.330
because people in
different cultures

00:49:15.330 --> 00:49:18.220
define happiness in
slightly different ways.

00:49:18.220 --> 00:49:23.740
And I think people in
the West, tend to favor--

00:49:23.740 --> 00:49:25.560
there's a word for
it, which has gone

00:49:25.560 --> 00:49:28.230
from my mind-- but very
high energy emotions

00:49:28.230 --> 00:49:32.880
like exhilaration, excitement,
real extreme emotions.

00:49:32.880 --> 00:49:34.780
And I think maybe in
some other cultures,

00:49:34.780 --> 00:49:37.700
they value a karma
contentment or whatever.

00:49:37.700 --> 00:49:39.600
There was some really
fascinating research

00:49:39.600 --> 00:49:41.790
that came out of UC
Berkeley recently,

00:49:41.790 --> 00:49:44.640
which looked at how
people defined happiness

00:49:44.640 --> 00:49:47.250
in different countries
around the world.

00:49:47.250 --> 00:49:52.920
And A, how they defined it, and
then B, how happy they were.

00:49:52.920 --> 00:49:59.080
And they found that in parts
of East Asia and in Russia,

00:49:59.080 --> 00:50:00.690
I think, that people
defined happiness

00:50:00.690 --> 00:50:01.980
in a much more collective way.

00:50:01.980 --> 00:50:03.563
So they didn't really
see it as a kind

00:50:03.563 --> 00:50:06.540
of individual pursuit in the
same way that we do in the US.

00:50:06.540 --> 00:50:10.140
But they saw it more as a
socially orientated endeavor.

00:50:10.140 --> 00:50:12.285
And for those people,
the more they--

00:50:12.285 --> 00:50:14.310
if you defined
happiness in that way,

00:50:14.310 --> 00:50:17.340
the more you pursued happiness,
the happier you became.

00:50:17.340 --> 00:50:19.950
Whereas in the US, where
people define happiness

00:50:19.950 --> 00:50:22.650
in a more individualistic way,
the more you pursue happiness,

00:50:22.650 --> 00:50:23.760
the less happy you become.

00:50:23.760 --> 00:50:25.930
So it's the opposite way.

00:50:25.930 --> 00:50:27.490
SPEAKER: Super fascinating.

